<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Dasa To Cut 3,000 Jobs by End of 1995 </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2903084894 Hamburg DER SPIEGEL in German 28 Mar 94 p 111 </F>
<F P=103> AU2903084894 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DER SPIEGEL </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Gloomy Forecasts for the Airbus"] </F>
  [Text] The Daimler-Benz subsidiary German Aerospace (Dasa) 
is in a worse state than had been thought until now. Two years 
ago, in drawing up their medium-term financial plans, Dasa 
managers assumed that their German Airbus subsidiary would 
deliver about 215 aircraft a year. A year ago, they had to 
adjust their forecast to about 180 aircraft a year -- according 
to their latest internal calculations, Airbus can only sell 120 
aircraft this year and next year. As a result, almost 3,000 
jobs are to be shed by the end of next year. From 1996 onward, 
Dasa managers expect Airbus sales to improve: If their 
calculations are wrong once again, there is a danger that more 
jobs will be lost. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

