<F P=100> CYPRUS </F>
<H3> <TI>   UN's Feissel Says Situation `Has Not Changed' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC2803194494 Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network in Greek 1600 GMT 28 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC2803194494 </F>
<F P=104>  Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Greek </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] During his meeting today with UN envoys Gustave 
Feissel and John Paul Cavanaugh, Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf 
Denktas maintained a negative and delaying stance. Following 
his afternoon meeting with Denktas, Feissel said the situation 
has not changed since last week and the United Nations did not 
receive the answer it wanted. He added that now is the time to 
prepare the report to the UN secretary general, who will make 
his own observations. 
  The UN secretary general's report to the Security Council on 
the progress of efforts to implement the confidence-building 
measures [CBM's] is expected to be submitted by the end of the 
month. 
  Answering a question on the topic, Feissel said he had 
personally asked for the meeting with Denktas and that no new 
meeting has been set. Asked whether there is a deadlock, 
Feissel said never and nothing is ever final but he added that 
it is relatively clear that the UN goal has not been achieved 
now. He said that he would brief President Glavkos Kliridhis on 
the outcome of the meeting but first he would inform the UN 
secretary general about the situation and what has happened in 
the past few weeks. 

</TEXT>

