<F P=100> FRANCE </F>
<H3> <TI>   FRY Foreign Minister Continues Visit </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2503180894 Belgrade Radio Beograd Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1400 GMT 25 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU2503180894 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade Radio Beograd Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Dusan Radovanovic from Paris] </F>
  [Text] Yugoslav Foreign Minister Vladislav Jovanovic, who 
has been paying a working visit to France at the invitation of 
the French foreign minister since yesterday, is today continuing 
talks with prominent French leaders. After very useful and 
frank talks with French Foreign Minister Alain Juppe last night 
on all aspects of the Yugoslav crisis, our foreign minister will 
today meet Hubert Vedrine, secretary general of the Elysee 
Palace, who is the closest associate of French President 
Mitterrand. 
  Jovanovic will also hold talks with General Schmid, personal 
adviser of the French prime minister for military issues, and 
(Savior Deviliten), chairman of the French Senate Commission for 
Foreign Affairs. In all the talks so far, especially with 
Foreign Minister Juppe, the Yugoslav foreign minister, as we 
have learned, stressed the discrepancy between French policies 
and the new reality in the Bosnian conflict and the Yugoslav 
crisis as a whole. He pointed out the need for Paris to carry 
out the necessary changes and to persuade both the European 
Union and the world community to adopt a more balanced approach, 
to abandon its selective policy, and to realize the advantages 
of treating all sides in the Yugoslav crisis in the same way. 
  In the context of the U.S. plan and the European initiative, 
the Yugoslav side stressed during all talks the untenability of 
the sanctions against the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia [FRY]. 
The sanctions represent an enormous obstacle to positive 
solutions. The Yugoslav side also noted that Yugoslavia has met 
all the demands contained in the European plan, while the 
European Union has completely ignored its obligations. 

</TEXT>

