<F P=100> ITALY &amp; VATICAN CITY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Prospects for Freedom Alliance Viewed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2903121094 Rome RAI Due Television Network in Italian 1100 
GMT 29 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2903121094 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome RAI Due Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Italian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Let us see what has changed in the political 
balance, and what will happen to the alliances in the future. 
Sergio De Luca reports: 
  [De Luca] It will not be easy to form a government, 
primarily 
because, as you have heard, the Freedom Alliance does not hold a 
majority of seats in the Senate. Silvio Berlusconi will be 
forced to turn to Mario Segni and Mino Martinazzoli in order to 
obtain the votes that he lacks. However, neither one seems very 
inclined to make an alliance with the Right. Segni and 
Martinazzoli seem to prefer being in opposition. 
  Berlusconi must then reckon with the Northern League. 
Umberto Bossi has already uttered two no's. He has said no to 
forming a government with Gianfranco Fini [National Alliance] 
and no to Berlusconi's candidacy for the post of prime minister. 
These are two formidable obstacles which Berlusconi must 
overcome. 
  It is difficult to make any forecasts at present. The 
postelection games have not even begun. However, it is clear 
that there will not be any clearcut choices and nor the 
stability which we expected from the new electoral system. 

</TEXT>

