<F P=100> AUSTRIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   General Opposes Sending Blue Helmets to Bosnia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2703131494 Vienna KURIER in German 26 Mar 94 p 4 </F>
<F P=103> AU2703131494 </F>
<F P=104>  Vienna KURIER </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Ingrid Steiner: "Austria Should Stay Out"] </F>
  [Text] In order to safeguard the Muslim-Croatian agreement 
and the six protective zones in Bosnia, the Blue Helmets are to 
be increased to 30,000 men. By sending 2,700 Turkish and 500 
Greek soldiers, for the first time "a UN principle is broken 
that says that neighboring states or countries with historically 
burdened relations do not send troops," Austrian General 
Guenther Greindl says. Greindl strictly opposes Austrian Blue 
Helmets for Bosnia: "Germans and some other nations should stay 
out of Bosnia. Austria was not asked by anyone to send 
soldiers." Instead, Austria has successfully provided equipment 
and humanitarian aid. 
  In Greindl's view, the UN mission in ex-Yugoslavia will drag 
on for decades "until the crisis is settled." In no case may 
borders be changed. "As soon as one border is redrawn, the 
entire Balkans begins to slide." One will probably have to 
tolerate ethnic cleansing within the republics. In every other 
respect, however, autonomy, the protection of human rights, and 
the further cooperation of the United States, Russia, and the 
European Union are the only way out of the crisis, Greindl noted. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

