<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   DPRK Ambassador Denies Country Preparing for War </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU3003100294 Vienna WIENER ZEITUNG in German 30 Mar 94 p 4 </F>
<F P=103> AU3003100294 </F>
<F P=104>  Vienna WIENER ZEITUNG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Korea: `Big Catastrophe' Imminent?"] </F>
  [Text] Vienna/Beijing -- The chances for a war in the 
Korean peninsula are "big" if the United States deploys Patriot 
missiles in South Korea and if it carries out the Team Spirit 
maneuvers, the North Korean ambassador to Austria, Kim 
Kwang-sop, has stated. North Korea is afraid of a military 
strike by South Korea, Kim stressed on Tuesday [29 March]. [as 
published] North Korea is strong enough to defend itself. 
Pyongyang pleads in favor of a peaceful solution to the 
conflict and is not preparing for a war. However, if a war 
should break out, it will "spread to other regions" and end in a 
"big catastrophe." 
  Kim rejected reports that his country is preparing for a 
war. 
"North Korea is a very small country and Korea is divided. How 
can we attack South Korea, the United States, or Japan? We do 
not understand the purpose of this propaganda." Yet the 
ambassador admitted that North Korea is in a position to produce 
missiles: "We have the possibility to produce missiles." 
However, numerous countries are able to do so. North Korea is 
not building nuclear weapons, he stated. 
  In the meantime, China has apparently been successful in 
rejecting sanctions and in demanding talks with the Stalinist 
country. During his visit to the PRC, South Korean President 
Kim Yong-sam stated in Beijing on Tuesday that he believes the 
problem can be solved smoothly through dialogue and negotiations. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

