<F P=100> INTER-EUROPEAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   EU Commissioner Delors Reserved on Ioannina Compromise </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR3003100194 Paris LE FIGARO in French 30 Mar 94 p 6 </F>
<F P=103> BR3003100194 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris LE FIGARO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Baudouin Bollaert report: "The Twelve Save Face"] </F>
  [Excerpt] [passage omitted] The European Commission itself 
did not make its opinion known [on the Ioannina voting rights 
compromise]. It will do so today when the permanent 
representatives of the Twelve meet in Brussels to "enact" the 
compromise. 
  Apparently, it will respond positively, although Jacques 
Delors is concerned about "negative jurisprudence" in the 
perspective of 1996 [EU institutional reforms]. Just two 
Commissioners yesterday expressed real reservations. One of 
them, Christiane Scrivener of France, spoke of "a dangerous and 
worrying step backward" compared with the progress made in the 
Single European Act of 1987. 
  Mrs. Scrivener knows full well the problems of finding a 
consensus, since her brief -- taxation -- is one of the last to 
require a unanimous vote. For her, the Ioannina compromise "is 
an attack on the qualified majority" while, on the contrary, an 
enlarged Europe needs a clearer "decisionmaking process." 
  Of course there is still the major review to come in 1996 
but, she says, "work will continue until at least 1998" and in 
the mean time Europe runs the risk of getting bogged down.... 

</TEXT>

