<H3> <TI>   Belgium's Claes Welcomes Accord on EU Compromise </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR3003120094 Brussels BELGA in French 1824 GMT 29 Mar 
94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR3003120094 </F>
<F P=104>  Brussels BELGA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Article signed LVE/PHF: "Willy Claes: The European Union </F>
Has Avoided Loss of Credibility"; as released by Brussels BELGA 
Database] 
  [Text] Istanbul 29 Mar (BELGA) -- Belgian Foreign Minister 
Willy Claes is very pleased at the United Kingdom's decision to 
accept the compromise submitted to the Twelve on Sunday [27 
March] by the Greek presidency of the European Union (EU) on the 
balance of votes within the enlarged Council of sixteen members. 
  "I am very pleased because we have been able to avoid at the 
very last minute what threatened to be a serious crisis which 
would have cost the EU much of its credibility," stressed Mr. 
Claes on Tuesday evening in Istanbul where he is completing an 
official two-day visit to Turkey. 
  The recantations of recent weeks suggest, however, that a 
difficult debate is likely at the 1996 intergovernmental 
conference on EU institutional reforms. 
  Mr. Claes nevertheless remains optimistic: "We showed on 
Sunday that we are able to provide satisfactory responses to 
very complex matters," he stated. 
  The Belgian foreign minister now wants to allow things to 
settle down and rejects the idea of quickly setting up a 
committee of wise men charged with clearing the way in 
preparation for 1996. 
  "We must not be too hasty. This committee should not start 
its activities until around mid-1995. It serves no purpose to 
immediately start a discussion between the different factions 
and therefore encumber the normal activities of the Community 
and the enlargement debates currently in progress with the four 
candidate countries," he added. 

</TEXT>

