<H3> <TI>   Cracks in Pipe Caused Leakage in Biblis Nuclear Plant </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2803145194 Hamburg DPA in German 1328 GMT 28 Mar 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2803145194 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Wiesbaden (DPA) -- Cracks in a steel pipe caused 
the latest incident in the controversial Biblis nuclear power 
plant in Hesse. This was reported by the Environment Ministry 
of the land in Wiesbaden on Monday [28 March]. The pipe in 
question in Block A, where contaminated water had leaked out 
from a pipe for the taking of samples, was checked. First 
results of a metallographical expert report of the 
Krafwerksunion (KWU) Company showed that the major number of 
cracks had probably been caused by chlorine, it was stated. 
  The nuclear supervisory board in Hesse took out a one-meter 
long section of the defective pipe of the pressure-keeping 
system. Part of it will be further checked in a Finnish 
material-testing laboratory. According to its own information, 
the Environment Ministry will only agree to repairs when the 
cause of the damage has been clarified without any doubt. 

</TEXT>

