<F P=101> Italy &amp; Vatican City </F>
<H3> <TI>   Aide: Forza Italia To Give Up `Pro-Arab' Policy </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR3003104494 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 2020 GMT 29 
Mar 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR3003104494 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Mideast/Italy: Go Italy Would </F>
Review Policies, Rivolta Says"] 
  [Text] (ANSA) Tel Aviv, March 29 -- A right-wing Italian 
government led by Go Italy [Forza Italia] would take a more 
"balanced" attitude towards Israel than past governments have, 
according to Dario Rivolta, a close aide of Go Italy leader 
Silvio Berlusconi. 
  In an interview with Israeli military radio on Tuesday [29 
March], Rivolta asserted that past Italian governments had a 
"pro-Arab and pro-Palestinian" foreign policy, adding: "That was 
the attitude of left-wing parties, which always tend to support 
the Arab political line." What Italy should do, Rivolta went on, 
is "to understand the true difficulties of the present situation 
and the seriousness of the obstacles blocking dialogue between 
Israelis and Palestinians." 
  Berlusconi last week told the Tel Aviv daily, YEDI'OT 
AHARONOT, that he was a true friend of Israel and praised the 
policies of Prime Minister Yitzhaq Rabin. 
  Interviewed by Israel's military radio, Israeli ambassador 
in 
Rome Avi Pazner denied Rivolta's claim that Italian foreign 
policy could be described as "pro-Arab." "For 2-3 years, in 
other words, since the start of the peace process, you can no 
longer talk about a pro-Arab Italian foreign policy," he said. 
"If anything, there is a policy in favour of peace, which 
includes expressions of friendship for Israel." 
  According to Pazner, after a conversation with the media 
mogul a couple of weeks ago, he believes that, if Berlusconi 
forms a government, he would expect it to be friendly towards 
Israel. "He's not about to form a clearly right-wing 
government," the diplomat said. "Even if he counts on 
right-wing support, Berlusconi is a man of the centre whose 
concerns include relations with Europe, the United States, 
Israel and also the Italian Jewish community." 

</TEXT>

