<F P=101> Italy &amp; Vatican City </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ciampi Hopes For `Climate of Stability' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR3003113394 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 1055 GMT 30 
Mar 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR3003113394 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Ciampi on Leaving; Disarray on the </F>
Victorious Right"] 
  [Excerpt] (ANSA) Rome, March 30 -- Premier Carlo Azeglio 
Ciampi told his cabinet today he looked forward to turning his 
office over to the new head of government as winner Silvio 
Berlusconi spoke of intentions to form a "political" executive 
and his key ally reiterated his total opposition to seeing 
Berlusconi in the premier's office. 
  Against the backdrop of the split between Berlusconi, the 
media mogul who led his three-month old Forza Italia to victory 
in the just-concluded general election, and Northern League 
leader Umberto Bossi, Ciampi said, "The government hopes to be 
able, as soon as possible, to hand matters on to the new 
government which will be named by the president of the republic 
on the basis of the electoral results." 
  The premier who took over in April last year, as the first 
non-politician and non-member of Parliament to hold this office, 
also spoke of hopes for "a climate of stability and correct 
civil co-existence, necessary conditions for facing the complex 
problems before the nation." He went on to voice "the 
satisfaction of the government with the orderly conduct of the 
campaign and voting operations which brought in the Parliament 
of the twelfth legislature. 
  ``The government,'' he added, ``is beginning to conclude its 
duties of management and as institutional guarantor in a 
sensitive phase of transition with results which testify to the 
country's basic steadiness and capacity for renewal in the 
political, economic and social fields and in democratic 
security.'' 
  In the wings, Berlusconi said all the alignments in his 
Forza 
Italia-led Freedom Front should be involved in the formation of 
a government, "just as indicated by the voters," and that the 
new executive should be "political" rather than a cabinet of 
"technocrats." [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

