<H3> <TI>   Leotard Deems NH-90 Helicopter Program `Essential' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR2503135494 Paris LE MONDE in French 25 Mar 94 p 11 </F>
<F P=103> BR2503135494 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris LE MONDE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Leotard Judges European NH-90 </F>
Helicopter Program `Essential' Despite Budget Constraints"] 
  [Text] In a letter to Olivier Darrason, UDF [French 
Democratic Union] deputy for Bouches-du-Rhone, assigned to study 
the NH-90 project, Defense Minister Leotard expressed his belief 
that the European NH-90 logistical helicopter program "is 
essential, both for the operational capability of our forces and 
for the future of the Eurocopter group. In addition," Leotard 
writes, "the government believes that aeronautics programs are a 
top priority. Despite current financial and budget 
difficulties, initial judgments by the prime minister on the 
military programming law will allow us to continue defense 
modernization." 
  Speaking to the National Assembly's Defense Committee, 
Jean-Francois Bigay, president of the Eurocopter group, pointed 
out that "the total cost of the NH-90 program would amount to 
ECU1.376 billion," more than 9 billion French francs [Fr]. 
French participation comes to 42.4 percent (Fr1.3 billion by 
Eurocopter and Fr3.9 billion by the state). "The unit cost of 
the NH-90 helicopter will be Fr85 million" for the Land Army 
version, "and Fr135 million" for the Navy version, Mr. Bigay 
specified. 
  The four countries participating in the program (France, 
Germany, The Netherlands, and Italy) have an overall requirement 
for 726 helicopters, while the non-European export market is 
estimated at approximately 500 "machines." The program is 
currently severely threatened by military budget cuts in the 
four participating countries. 

</TEXT>

