<F P=100> ITALY &amp; VATICAN CITY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Scalfaro Hopes for `Stability' Following Elections </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU3003063794 Paris AFP in English 2029 GMT 29 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU3003063794 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Rome, March 29 (AFP) -- President Oscar Luigi 
Scalfaro said Tuesday [29 March] that he hoped Italy's next 
parliament would "guarantee stablility for policies and 
stability for the Italian people." 
  Scalfaro, who will designate the next head of government 
following the landslide victory by a right-wing bloc headed by 
media magnate Silvio Berlusconi, said in a statement to the 
press that the new administration "was entitled to work in 
peace." 
  He hailed the climate of "tranquility and normality" in 
which 
the election had been conducted despite a complex new electoral 
law. 
  Scalfaro is to convene a meeting on April 15 of the new 
chambers of Italy's 12th legislature since World War II. 

</TEXT>

