<F P=100> ITALY &amp; VATICAN CITY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Berlusconi Offers To Sell Media Assets </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU3003104994 Paris AFP in English 1030 GMT 30 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU3003104994 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Milan, March 30 (AFP) -- Media magnate Silvio 
Berlusconi, the main victor in Italy's legislative elections, 
has offered to sell one of his television networks to ease 
opposition to his forming a new government. 
  Berlusconi has said he wants to become prime minister 
following the landslide election victory Monday [28 March] of 
the rightwing alliance led by his Forza Italia party. 
  But a key coalition partner, Umberto Bossi of the Northern 
League, has objected that Berlusconi's vast financial and media 
holdings made him unsuited to lead a government. 
  Questioned during a television interview late Tuesday about 
Bossi's remarks, Berlusconi replied, "If I could find someone 
ready to buy, I could give up one of my television stations." 
  Burlusconi's huge conglomerate, Fininvest, owns three 
national television networks as well as other media, 
telecommunications, property and distribution holdings. 
  He also said he was willing to sell other unidentified 
"companies" in the Fininvest group. 
  When he entered the political campaign last January, 
Berlusconi handed the presidency of Fininvest over to an 
associate. 
  The right-wing coalition that won a majority in Italy's 
latest election comprises Berlusconi's Forza Italy party, the 
federalist Northern League and the neo-facist party National 
Alliance. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

