<F P=100> CYPRUS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rasid Reacts to Mikhailidhis on Deadlock in Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC2903184494 Nicosia KIBRIS in Turkish 29 Mar 94 p 3 </F>
<F P=103> NC2903184494 </F>
<F P=104>  Nicosia KIBRIS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Turkish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Atay Ahmet Rasid, minister of foreign affairs and 
defense, has said that the Greek Cypriot side must quickly 
abandon its inflexible approach and refrain from making 
statements and accusations against the Turkish Cypriot side that 
are aimed at misleading the public, so that a balanced and just 
result can be achieved from the talks that are being held on the 
confidence-building measures. 
  In a written statement yesterday, Rasid recalled Greek 
Cypriot Foreign Minister Alexandros Mikhailidhis' effort to 
blame the Turkish Cypriot side for the deadlock in the talks on 
the confidence-building measures and said that Mikhailidhis' 
effort was aimed at distorting well-known facts. 
  Rasid stressed that the introduction of new elements in the 
talks -- elements aimed at satisfying the Greek Cypriot side -- 
will create a deadlock in the negotiating process. He said: 
"As the experts who follow the talks on the confidence-building 
measures on Maras [Varosha] and the Nicosia International 
Airport have seen, the main reasons for the present deadlock are 
the Greek Cypriot side's pressure and the attempt to deviate 
from the original package of confidence-building measures and 
add new elements to it in order to satisfy Glavkos Kliridhis and 
the Greek Cypriot side." 

</TEXT>

