<H3> <TI>   Foreign Minister, U.S. Envoy Comment on Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC2903200794 Athens ET-1 Television Network in Greek 1820 
GMT 29 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC2903200794 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens ET-1 Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Greek </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Statements by Foreign Minister Karolos Papoulias and </F>
Matthew Nimetz, U.S. special presidential envoy, after their 
meeting at the Foreign Ministry in Athens; Nimetz speaks in 
English with superimposed Greek translation; broadcast in 
progress--live] 
  [Text] [Papoulias] ...the problem of relations between 
Greece and The Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia [FYROM]. 
We welcome the U.S. efforts to find a solution or a way out of 
the deadlock. Our talks could be described as positive. This is 
our first meeting and I am sure there will be more. Nimetz will 
continue his talks with the prime minister. 
  I believe this is what I could tell you now as the initial 
result of a first meeting that is over traditional frameworks 
and frameworks of simple meetings. Thank you. 
  [Nimetz] I am greatly honored that President Clinton has 
asked me to take on this significant mission. This dispute 
threatens the security and stability in a region that is very 
important to the United States. We had discussions this morning 
in Skopje and we had discussions here. And we will continue the 
discussions. 
  Our goal is to assist in achieving a solution under the 
auspices of UN mediator Cyrus Vance. I do not think I will say 
anything more. We will persevere in this effort and I hope the 
outcome will be positive. 

