<F P=100> GREECE </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. Said To Want Swift Solution on FYROM </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC2903201294 Athens ELEVTHEROTIPIA in Greek 29 Mar 94 p 4 </F>
<F P=103> NC2903201294 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens ELEVTHEROTIPIA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Greek </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Kira Adham] </F>
  [Excerpt] The United States is in a hurry for a solution to 
the issue of The Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia [FYROM] 
and agreed to separate the name issue from the initial phase of 
dialogue. Therefore, during his meeting with EU Commissioner 
Hans van den Broek yesterday, Prime Minister Andreas Papandreou 
found it easier to reject the European Union's [EU] unilateral 
mediation effort. 
  Reliable information and the recent talks between Deputy 
Foreign Minister Yeoryios Papandreou and his U.S. counterpart in 
the United States indicate that the U.S. Government is in a 
hurry to resolve the issue of FYROM, claiming that [FYROM 
President Kiro] Gligorov's state may collapse. 
<H5>  Name Separation </H5>
  According to the same information, the Americans made it 
clear to the Greek side that they want very much to see the 
issue of FYROM resolved as soon as possible so that they can 
jointly (Greece and the United States) "discuss regional 
cooperation in the Balkans." 
  The United States also seemed to have accepted the Greek 
position to separate FYROM's name from the initial phase of the 
dialogue, because maintaining stability in the region is more 
important. 
  The same sources said that Washington did not put pressure 
on 
Athens to lift the Greek measures, but expressed the "wish" that 
"something would be done" in this direction. 
  Diplomatic sources mentioned that Ambassador Matthew Nimetz, 
President Clinton's special envoy to Skopje, (who will meet the 
prime minister and the foreign minister today and will later go 
to FYROM), will undertake a very important mediation role and 
will have an "open line" to UN mediator Cyrus Vance. 
  According to the same information, Vance--as he had 
said--intends to deal with the "substance of the issue," that 
is, bring the two sides back to the negotiating table. Nimetz 
will undertake the "details" (conditions, requirements, etc.). 
  On the eve of the United States' active involvement in the 
issue of FYROM, the government essentially "stopped" the EU 
unilateral mediation effort. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

