<F P=100> Denmark </F>
<H3> <TI>   Poll Shows Losses for CD, SDP </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM2903120094 Copenhagen BERLINGSKE TIDENDE SONDAG in Danish 
27 Mar 94 p 3 </F>

<F P=103> PM2903120094 </F>
<F P=104>  Copenhagen BERLINGSKE TIDENDE SONDAG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Danish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Erik Bjorn Moller report: "Center Democrats Fall Below </F>
Threshold"] 
  [Text] The governing party, the Center Democrats [CD], 
again has fallen below the threshold for representation in the 
Folketing. However, the Social Democratic Party [SDP] is unable 
to understand the party's major losses in this months Gallup 
opinion poll. 
  It is understandable that the Center Democrats should be 
losing voters after the infamous affair involving Bente Juncker, 
the former social affairs minister who accused the head of an 
institution of the sexual abuse of the mentally subnormal. 
  Such are the comments from several Social Democrats after 
BERLINGSKE TIDENDE's new Gallup poll today. On the other hand 
they are unable to understand why the Social Democrats have lost 
more than 4.2 percent of voter support since the February poll. 
  However, Interior Minister Birte Weiss (Social Democratic 
Party) is well able to understand why the Liberal Party is 
"slowly but surely" continuing its downturn -- this time from 
26.9 percent to 25.8 percent of votes. "The closer we come to 
the elections, the greater will be the nervousness of those 
drifting voters who have sought refuge with the Liberal Party," 
Interior Minister Birte Weiss said. She also said that Liberal 
Party chairman Uffe Ellemann-Jensen's "unsavory manner" is 
gradually causing voters to beg off. 
  Conservative People's Party leader Hans Engell is extremely 
satisfied with his party's continued success. He stressed that 
"people must now count on a Liberal-Conservative-Progress Party 
majority as a real possibility." And he believes that Prime 
Minister Poul Nyrup Rasmussen is facing a reverse "prime 
minister effect" [the effect of increased support in opinion 
polls for the party providing the prime minister in a coalition 
government]: 
  "There is much to indicate that Nyrup Rasmussen is pulling 
everything down for the Social Democrats," Engell said. 


