<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Owen, Stoltenberg Brief Peace Conference on Bosnia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU3003163994 Paris AFP in English 1628 GMT 30 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU3003163994 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Geneva, March 30 (AFP) -- International mediators 
Lord Owen and Thorvald Stoltenberg, briefing colleagues 
Wednesday [30 March] on developments in peace talks for former 
Yugoslavia, said they were pleased with progress but serious 
problems still lay ahead. 
  The main issues remain the scope of reconstruction needed to 
put the devastated region back on its feet and the maps that 
must still be drawn for peace accords reached this month under 
combined U.S.- Russian diplomatic pressure. 
  "The pattern is encouraging, but now the crucial thing is 
the 
map," European Union negotiator Owen told journalists after a 
meeting of the steering committee of the Geneva Peace Conference 
on former Yugoslavia, which groups around 30 countries and 
organisations. 
  Owen, just back from weekend talks in Belgrade, said Serbian 
President Slobodan Milosevic was showing flexibility. 
  Serbia wanted to reach agreement on an effective ceasefire, 
restoration of economic relations with neighbouring countries 
and the lifting of the international blockade against its rump 
state of Yugoslavia, he said. 
  The consultations came as the peace process received a boost 
after Bosnian Croats and Moslems signed a federation agreement 
in Washington on March 18 and Croatia and Serb separatists from 
the breakaway Krajina enclave signed a ceasefire accord early 
Wednesday. 
  "One of the most fundamental things is not to get much 
delay. 
This momentum is very, very important," Owen said at a press 
conference, praising the involvement of the two superpowers in 
the peace process. 
  The Bosnian Serbs are now considering whether they should 
join the Croat-Moslem entente, which they feared "could be an 
anti-Serb alliance," explained Owen. 
  U.S. special Envoy Charles Redman, who helped conclude that 
agreement, should visit the Bosnian Serb stronghold of Pale 
Wednesday or Thursday, said Owen, who thought the problem should 
be resolved jointly by the United Nations, the European Union, 
the United States and Russia. 
  Members of the Geneva steering committee, speaking about the 
mammoth task of rebuilding the war-ravaged region, said it was 
important that international aid efforts did not substitute for 
the efforts of the countries concerned, leaving them free to arm 
themselves once more. 
  The United States has made some aid promises but there is 
little doubt that the European Union will have to shoulder the 
main burden, members said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

